d well-credentialed lawyers of their respective generations, female nominees and nominees of color face more skepticism of their professional competence, are subjected to stereotype-based questioning, are more frequently interrupted, and are described in less-positive terms by senators. In addition to revealing the disturbing extent to which race and gender bias exist even at the highest echelon of U.S. legal power, this book also provides concrete suggestions for how that bias can be reduced in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBias (Law)zUnited States2DLC. 0aBias (Law)zUnited States. 0aDiscrimination in justice administrationzUnited States2DLC. 0aDiscrimination in justice administrationzUnited States. 0aJudgesxSelection and appointmentzUnited States2DLC. 0aJudgesxSelection and appointmentzUnited States. 0aLegislative hearingszUnited States2DLC. 0aLegislative hearingszUnited States. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States2DLC. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aSex discrimination against womenxLaw and legislationzUnited States2DLC. 0aSex discrimination against womenxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 7aLAW / Gender & the Law.2bisacsh  aJudiciary Committee.  aSenate.  aSupreme Court.  abias.  aconfirmation.  agender.  ainequality.  ajustice.  anomination.  arace.1 aBoyd, Christina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRinghand, Lori, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023 Englishz978311